[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":227},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjs-weird-world-14-primitive-values\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjs-weird-world-14-primitive-values\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjs-weird-world-14-primitive-values\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjs-weird-world-14-primitive-values\u002F":203,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjs-weird-world-14-primitive-values\u002F":212},"\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F20190516\u002F890725015\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":185,"date":186,"description":187,"extension":188,"lang":189,"meta":190,"navigation":191,"path":192,"readingMinutes":193,"seo":194,"standalone":195,"stem":196,"tags":197,"tldr":200,"updated":186,"url":201,"__hash__":202},"content\u002Fen\u002FJsWeirdWorld\u002Fjs-weird-world-14-primitive-values.md","[JS Weird World] No.14 Primitive Values: The Six Types JavaScript Actually Has","1000039598",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":173},"minimark",[11,16,23,26,29,32,36,43,54,64,73,77,93,103,107,111,114,121,125,128,132,136,139,143,147,153,157,160,164],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"primitive-values","Primitive Values",[17,18,19],"p",{},[20,21],"img",{"alt":15,"src":22},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FHFn5EJEh.png",[17,24,25],{},"We've already done a quick intro to JavaScript's types. This chapter digs deeper — into JavaScript's dynamic typing, what it is, and what its upsides and downsides are.",[17,27,28],{},"First off, what's a primitive value? A primitive is a kind of data type — it represents a single value, not an object. (Remember, an object is a collection of name\u002Fvalue pairs.)",[17,30,31],{},"And JavaScript has six types in total.",[12,33,35],{"id":34},"undefined","Undefined",[17,37,38,39,42],{},"We've already mentioned ",[40,41,34],"code",{}," countless times by now, so you've probably got a decent feel for it. But what does it actually mean?",[44,45,46],"blockquote",{},[17,47,48,49,53],{},"Undefined means this value ",[50,51,52],"strong",{},"hasn't been assigned a value yet",".",[17,55,56,57,60,61,63],{},"It's the ",[50,58,59],{},"initial value"," JavaScript gives to every variable. So I'll say it again — never manually set a variable to ",[40,62,34],{},". JavaScript does let you do it, but it'll make debugging harder down the road.",[65,66,72],"iframe",{"height":67,"style":68,"scrolling":69,"title":35,"src":70,"frameBorder":69,"allowTransparency":71,"allowFullScreen":71},265,"width: 100%;","no","\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng\u002Fembed\u002FmYLLOe\u002F?height=265&theme-id=0&default-tab=js,result","true","\n  See the Pen \u003Ca href='https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng\u002Fpen\u002FmYLLOe\u002F'>Undefined\u003C\u002Fa> by HF\n  (\u003Ca href='https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng'>@hsiangfeng\u003C\u002Fa>) on \u003Ca href='https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io'>CodePen\u003C\u002Fa>.\n",[12,74,76],{"id":75},"null","Null",[17,78,79,80,84,85,87,88,90,91,53],{},"Null is like Undefined in that both mean \"doesn't exist.\" But the difference is, you ",[81,82,83],"em",{},"can"," set a variable to ",[40,86,75],{},". So in real-world dev, you'd use ",[40,89,75],{}," to assign a value rather than ",[40,92,34],{},[94,95,96,100],"ul",{},[97,98,99],"li",{},"Null semantically means empty",[97,101,102],{},"undefined means the variable hasn't been assigned a value yet",[65,104,106],{"height":67,"style":68,"scrolling":69,"title":76,"src":105,"frameBorder":69,"allowTransparency":71,"allowFullScreen":71},"\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng\u002Fembed\u002FBexxpQ\u002F?height=265&theme-id=0&default-tab=js,result","\n  See the Pen \u003Ca href='https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng\u002Fpen\u002FBexxpQ\u002F'>Null\u003C\u002Fa> by HF\n  (\u003Ca href='https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng'>@hsiangfeng\u003C\u002Fa>) on \u003Ca href='https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io'>CodePen\u003C\u002Fa>.\n",[12,108,110],{"id":109},"boolean","Boolean",[17,112,113],{},"This one's familiar to pretty much everyone, so I won't say much.",[94,115,116,118],{},[97,117,71],{},[97,119,120],{},"false",[12,122,124],{"id":123},"number","Number",[17,126,127],{},"JavaScript has just one numeric type: Number. Other languages might have separate integer and float types, but JavaScript only has Number — and Number is actually a Float, so it can handle decimals just fine.",[65,129,131],{"height":67,"style":68,"scrolling":69,"title":124,"src":130,"frameBorder":69,"allowTransparency":71,"allowFullScreen":71},"\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng\u002Fembed\u002FMdGGmG\u002F?height=265&theme-id=0&default-tab=js,result","\n  See the Pen \u003Ca href='https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng\u002Fpen\u002FMdGGmG\u002F'>Number\u003C\u002Fa> by HF\n  (\u003Ca href='https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng'>@hsiangfeng\u003C\u002Fa>) on \u003Ca href='https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io'>CodePen\u003C\u002Fa>.\n",[12,133,135],{"id":134},"string","String",[17,137,138],{},"Next up is something you'll see all the time — strings. In short, anything wrapped in single or double quotes is a string.",[65,140,142],{"height":67,"style":68,"scrolling":69,"title":135,"src":141,"frameBorder":69,"allowTransparency":71,"allowFullScreen":71},"\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng\u002Fembed\u002FmYLLwV\u002F?height=265&theme-id=0&default-tab=js,result","\n  See the Pen \u003Ca href='https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng\u002Fpen\u002FmYLLwV\u002F'>String\u003C\u002Fa> by HF\n  (\u003Ca href='https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng'>@hsiangfeng\u003C\u002Fa>) on \u003Ca href='https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io'>CodePen\u003C\u002Fa>.\n",[12,144,146],{"id":145},"symbol","Symbol",[17,148,149,150,152],{},"This one's a bit special. It's called Symbol, and it was added in ES6. You don't run into it much in practice, and you have to create one through the ",[40,151,146],{}," function — so it's kind of an unusual case.",[65,154,156],{"height":67,"style":68,"scrolling":69,"title":146,"src":155,"frameBorder":69,"allowTransparency":71,"allowFullScreen":71},"\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng\u002Fembed\u002FVOxxzY\u002F?height=265&theme-id=0&default-tab=js,result","\n  See the Pen \u003Ca href='https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng\u002Fpen\u002FVOxxzY\u002F'>Symbol\u003C\u002Fa> by HF\n  (\u003Ca href='https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng'>@hsiangfeng\u003C\u002Fa>) on \u003Ca href='https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io'>CodePen\u003C\u002Fa>.\n",[17,158,159],{},"And that's the six main types (primitive values) in JavaScript.",[12,161,163],{"id":162},"image-source","Image source",[17,165,166],{},[167,168,172],"a",{"href":169,"rel":170},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.udemy.com\u002Fjavascriptjs\u002F",[171],"nofollow","JavaScript 全攻略:克服 JS 奇怪的部分",{"title":174,"searchDepth":175,"depth":175,"links":176},"",2,[177,178,179,180,181,182,183,184],{"id":14,"depth":175,"text":15},{"id":34,"depth":175,"text":35},{"id":75,"depth":175,"text":76},{"id":109,"depth":175,"text":110},{"id":123,"depth":175,"text":124},{"id":134,"depth":175,"text":135},{"id":145,"depth":175,"text":146},{"id":162,"depth":175,"text":163},"JsWeirdWorld","2019-05-16 19:30:35","We've already done a quick intro to JavaScript's types. This chapter goes deeper into JavaScript's dynamic typing — what it is, and what its pros and cons are. Along the way we'll walk through the six primitive types: Undefined, Null, Boolean, Number, String, and Symbol.","md","en",{},true,"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002Fjs-weird-world-14-primitive-values","2",{"title":6,"description":187},false,"en\u002FJsWeirdWorld\u002Fjs-weird-world-14-primitive-values",[198,199],"JavaScript","JavaScript 全攻略:克服JS奇怪的部分",null,"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjs-weird-world-14-primitive-values\u002F","Lm8MzLcCaiA55rXfNErbex8L4Hv0Zqwvz3THvTMvyCQ",{"newer":204,"older":208},{"url":205,"title":206,"date":207},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjsweirdworld-15-operators\u002F","[JS Weird World] No.15 Quick Reminder: Operators Are Secretly Functions","2019-05-16 20:00:35",{"url":209,"title":210,"date":211},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjsweirdworld-13-types-and-javascript\u002F","[JS Weird World] No.13 Quick Concept Check — Types and JavaScript","2019-05-16 19:00:35",[213,218,223],{"url":214,"title":215,"date":216,"readingMinutes":217},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F27\u002Fjs-weird-world-bonus-closures\u002F","[JS Weird World] Bonus: Closures, One More Time","2019-05-27 13:50:04","5",{"url":219,"title":220,"date":221,"readingMinutes":222},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F25\u002Fjs-weird-world-68-the-end-is-a-new-beginning\u002F","[JS Weird World] No.68 Wrapping Up the Weird Parts of JavaScript","2019-05-25 16:36:00","1",{"url":224,"title":225,"date":226,"readingMinutes":193},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F25\u002Fjs-weird-world-67-adding-jquery-support\u002F","[JS Weird World] No.67 Adding jQuery Support to Our Mini Framework","2019-05-25 16:19:00",1784012778080]